            <fr:title text="Abstract Chinese Remainder Theorem">Abstract Chinese Remainder Theorem</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="source">Dummit and Foote <fr:link href="/dummit-2004-abstract/" title="Abstract Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/dummit-2004-abstract/" display-uri="dummit-2004-abstract" type="local">Abstract Algebra</fr:link> Theorem 7.6.17</fr:meta>
            <fr:meta name="source">Hungerford <fr:link href="/hungerford-1974-algebra/" title="Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/hungerford-1974-algebra/" display-uri="hungerford-1974-algebra" type="local">Algebra</fr:link> Theorem III.2.25</fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="/ring-0001/" title="Ring" uri="http://localhost:8000/ring-0001/" display-uri="ring-0001" type="local">Ring</fr:link>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex> be <fr:link href="/ra-0024/" title="Comaximal ideals" uri="http://localhost:8000/ra-0024/" display-uri="ra-0024" type="local">comaximal</fr:link> <fr:link href="/ra-0011/" title="Ideal" uri="http://localhost:8000/ra-0011/" display-uri="ra-0011" type="local">two-sided ideals</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>. Then
<html:ol><html:li>the map
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[R/(I\cap  J)\to  (R/I)\times (R/J)]]></fr:tex>
defined by sending <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\mapsto (x+I,x+J)]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link href="/ra-000X/" title="Ring Isomorphism" uri="http://localhost:8000/ra-000X/" display-uri="ra-000X" type="local">Ring Isomorphism</fr:link>; and</html:li>
<html:li>furthermore if we write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I\cdot  J=\langle \{ab\in  R\mid  a\in  I,b\in  J\}\rangle ]]></fr:tex> for the two-sided ideal generated by products of elements of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I\cdot  J=I\cap  J]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ol></html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>18</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>(1) Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi \colon  R\to (R/I)\times (R/J)]]></fr:tex> be the mapping such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi (x)=(x+I,x+J)]]></fr:tex> for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  R]]></fr:tex>. Its kernel is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I\cap  J]]></fr:tex>. Then by the <fr:link href="/ra-0018/" title="First Isomorphism Theorem for Rings" uri="http://localhost:8000/ra-0018/" display-uri="ra-0018" type="local">first isomorphism theorem</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi '\colon  R/(I\cap  J)\to (R/I)\times (R/J)]]></fr:tex> is injective because it has a trivial kernel. We need to show it is surjective.</html:p>
<html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(u+I,v+J)\in (R/I)\times (R/J)]]></fr:tex>, we want to find <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  R]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi (x)=(u+I,v+J)]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  I]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  J]]></fr:tex> be such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a+b=1]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x=va+ub]]></fr:tex>, so we can check <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi '(x)=(a+A,b+B)]]></fr:tex>. We find
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {align*}x
&\equiv  ub\bmod {I}\\
&\equiv  (1-a)u\bmod {I}\\
&\equiv  u\bmod {I}\end {align*}]]></fr:tex>
and similarly <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\equiv  v\bmod {B}]]></fr:tex> as desired.</html:p>
<html:p>(2) Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex> are comaximal, there exists <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  I]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  J]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a+b=1]]></fr:tex>. We want to show <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I\cap  J\subseteq  I\cdot  J]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  I\cap  J]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x=x\cdot 1=xa+xb]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[xa\in  JI]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[xb\in  IJ]]></fr:tex>, hence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  I\cdot  J]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
<html:p>We see <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I\cap  J\supseteq  I\cdot  J]]></fr:tex> obviously.</html:p>
<html:span class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
