            <fr:title text="Unique Factorization Domain">Unique Factorization Domain</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="source">MML <fr:link href="https://mizar.uwb.edu.pl/version/current/html/ring_2.html#V8" type="external">ring_2:def 15</fr:link></fr:meta>
            <fr:meta name="source">Hungerford <fr:link href="/hungerford-1974-algebra/" title="Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/hungerford-1974-algebra/" display-uri="hungerford-1974-algebra" type="local">Algebra</fr:link> Definition III.3.5</fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>An <fr:link href="/ra-000H/" title="Integral domain" uri="http://localhost:8000/ra-000H/" display-uri="ra-000H" type="local">Integral domain</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is called a <html:dfn>Unique Factorization Domain</html:dfn> (or UFD for short, older texts say <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is <html:dfn>Factorial</html:dfn>) if
<html:ol><html:li>Nonzero elements have a Factorization: For every nonzero element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in R^{*}]]></fr:tex> there exists a factorization
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[a=u\prod ^{N}_{j=1}p_{j}^{n_{j}}]]></fr:tex>
where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in R^{\times }]]></fr:tex> is a unit, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p_{j}\in  R]]></fr:tex> are distinct <fr:link href="/ra-001U/" title="Irreducible element" uri="http://localhost:8000/ra-001U/" display-uri="ra-001U" type="local">irreducitlbe elements</fr:link>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n_{j}\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> are positive integers; and</html:li>
<html:li>Factorizations are unique: For every nonzero element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in R^{*}]]></fr:tex> if there are two factorizations
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[a=u\prod ^{N}_{j=1}p_{j}^{n_{j}}]]></fr:tex>
and
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[a=v\prod ^{N'}_{j=1}q_{j}^{m_{j}}]]></fr:tex>
then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N=N']]></fr:tex> and there exists a permutation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma \in  S_{N}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u_{j}p_{j}=q_{\sigma (j)}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n_{j}=m_{\sigma (j)}]]></fr:tex> for units <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u_{j}\in R^{\times }]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ol></html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
