            <fr:title text="Prime Ideal">Prime Ideal</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="/ra-0003/" title="Commutative Ring" uri="http://localhost:8000/ra-0003/" display-uri="ra-0003" type="local">Commutative Ring</fr:link>. An <fr:link href="/ra-0011/" title="Ideal" uri="http://localhost:8000/ra-0011/" display-uri="ra-0011" type="local">ideal</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P\mathrel {\trianglelefteq } R]]></fr:tex> is <html:dfn>Quasi-Prime</html:dfn> if for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a,b\in  R]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ab\in  P]]></fr:tex>, then either <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  P]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  P]]></fr:tex>.</html:p><html:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P\mathrel {\triangleleft } R]]></fr:tex> is a proper quasi-prime ideal, then we say it is a <html:dfn>Prime Ideal</html:dfn>.</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>17</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>remark</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>(1) This notion does not generalize to noncommutative rings. If we tried "naively" looking for ideals of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathop {\mathrm {Mat}}\nolimits _{2}(\mathbb {C})]]></fr:tex> which are prime, then we will not find any. It remains an open problem how to define prime ideals for noncommutative rings.</html:p>
<html:p>(2) Hungerford <fr:link href="/hungerford-1974-algebra/" title="Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/hungerford-1974-algebra/" display-uri="hungerford-1974-algebra" type="local">Algebra</fr:link> Exercise 9(b) in Section III.2 asks the reader to prove: if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> is a division ring and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R=\mathop {\mathrm {Mat}}\nolimits _{n}(D)]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> has zero divisors and so the trivial ideal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(0)]]></fr:tex> is prime, which means <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R\cong  R/(0)]]></fr:tex> but <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is not an integral domain. This is because <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is not a commutative ring. (See? Things get really weird when trying to think about prime ideals in a noncommutative ring.)</html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
