            <fr:title text="Traditional way of teaching abstract algebra">Traditional way of teaching abstract algebra</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>The traditional way we teach undergraduates is by introducing several types of gadgets in abstract algebra in the following order:</html:p>
            <html:ol><html:li>Initially, there's some discussion of set theory sufficient for developing algebra. This is "time honored tradition" starting with van der Waerden's book.</html:li>
<html:li>When the structure-preserving transformations leave something invariant (e.g., <fr:link href="/vectsp-001P/" title="Invariant subspace" uri="http://localhost:8000/vectsp-001P/" display-uri="vectsp-001P" type="local">Invariant subspace</fr:link>s in linear algebra), composing such transformations also leaves the thing invariant. This is the guiding intuition of what a "symmetry" is, and the "collection of symmetries" is precisely what a "group" is (originally, they were a "group of symmetries" or a <html:em>symmetry group</html:em>).</html:li>
<html:li><html:p>(a) But we also saw how, e.g., square matrices have a neat <fr:link href="/ela-000B/" title="Matrix Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/ela-000B/" display-uri="ela-000B" type="local">algebraic structure</fr:link> with matrix addition and matrix multiplication. They act like a "number system". This is precisely what is studied with number ring (or just a <fr:link href="/ring-0001/" title="Ring" uri="http://localhost:8000/ring-0001/" display-uri="ring-0001" type="local">Ring</fr:link>). A sufficiently nice ring is a <fr:link href="/field-0001/" title="Field" uri="http://localhost:8000/field-0001/" display-uri="field-0001" type="local">Field</fr:link>.</html:p>
<html:p>(b) We can generalize linear algebra to describe "vector spaces over arbitrary rings", and these are modules.</html:p></html:li>
<html:li>Galois theory is offered as the pinnacle of abstract algebra, connecting group theory to field theory. Honestly, I never understood the excitement behind Galois theory, since the beautiful parts of it are just the representation theory of groups (describing how "the same symmetries appearing in different situations").</html:li></html:ol>
            <html:p>This is just the first 7 chapters of van der Waerden's <fr:link href="/van-der-waerden-1949-modern1/" title="Modern Algebra, Vol. I" uri="http://localhost:8000/van-der-waerden-1949-modern1/" display-uri="van-der-waerden-1949-modern1" type="local">Modern Algebra, Vol. I</fr:link>. Most textbooks have followed this manner of presentation: Dummit and Foote's <fr:link href="/dummit-2004-abstract/" title="Abstract Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/dummit-2004-abstract/" display-uri="dummit-2004-abstract" type="local">Abstract Algebra</fr:link> covers this material in the first 14 chapters; Hungerford's <fr:link href="/hungerford-1974-algebra/" title="Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/hungerford-1974-algebra/" display-uri="hungerford-1974-algebra" type="local">Algebra</fr:link> does this in the first 6 chapters.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
