            <fr:title text="Dihedral group">Dihedral group</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="source">Dummit and Foote <fr:link href="/dummit-2004-abstract/" title="Abstract Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/dummit-2004-abstract/" display-uri="dummit-2004-abstract" type="local">Abstract Algebra</fr:link> Section 1.2</fr:meta>
            <fr:meta name="source">Hungerford <fr:link href="/hungerford-1974-algebra/" title="Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/hungerford-1974-algebra/" display-uri="hungerford-1974-algebra" type="local">Algebra</fr:link> Theorem 1.6.13</fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> be a positive integer. We define the <html:dfn>Dihedral group</html:dfn> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D_{n}]]></fr:tex> to consist of the set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{x^{k}y^{j}\mid  0\leq  k<n,0\leq  j\leq  1\}]]></fr:tex> where we also write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x^{0}y^{0}=1]]></fr:tex>, such that
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[x^{n}=y^{2}=1]]></fr:tex>
and also
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[yx=x^{-1}y.]]></fr:tex>
It's not hard to see <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[yx^{k}=x^{-k}y]]></fr:tex> by applying that second relation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex> times.</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>13</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>remark</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>(1) The dihedral group describes the symmetries of the regular <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-gon in the plane, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> is rotation anticlockwise by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2\pi  / n]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> is reflection about a line through the origin.</html:p>
<html:p>(2) Some authors (like Dummit and Foote) call this group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D_{2n}]]></fr:tex> because it is of <fr:link href="/gr-000P/" title="Order of a group" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-000P/" display-uri="gr-000P" type="local">order</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2n]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
<html:p>(3) <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D_{1}]]></fr:tex> has <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x=1]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D_{0}]]></fr:tex> is degenerate.</html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
